pr_body:
# Functionality discussion: 
 * https://discourse.joplinapp.org/t/mobile-image-editor-prototype/26769

# Summary
 * This PR adds:
     * an option to draw an image after clicking `attach` in the mobile app.
     * re-maps the `open` long-press menu item to edit drawn images (currently determined by images with `mime: image/svg+xml`).

# To-do (for **this** PR)
 * Fix occasional NaN error while stroke smoothing
 * Add tests for loading/saving
 * Detect if an SVG wasn't made in Joplin and warn the user?
     * There can be some path-related data loss (the editor doesn't support some path commands), but otherwise the editor preserves unrecognized SVG tags. ...so perhaps this isn't necessary?


<!--

Please prefix the title with the platform you are targetting:

Here are some examples of good titles:

- Desktop: Resolves #123: Added new setting to change font
- Mobile, Desktop: Fixes #456: Fixed config screen error
- All: Resolves #777: Made synchronisation faster

And here's an explanation of the title format:

- "Desktop" for the Windows/macOS/Linux app (Electron app)
- "Mobile" for the mobile app (or "Android" / "iOS" if the pull request only applies to one of the mobile platforms)
- "CLI" for the CLI app

If it's two platforms, separate them with commas - "Desktop, Mobile" or if it's for all platforms, prefix with "All".

If it's not related to any platform (such as a translation, change to the documentation, etc.), simply don't add a platform.

Then please append the issue that you've addressed or fixed. Use "Resolves #123" for new features or improvements and "Fixes #123" for bug fixes.

AND PLEASE READ THE GUIDE: https://github.com/laurent22/joplin/blob/dev/CONTRIBUTING.md

-->

# Summary
 * Adds a markdown toolbar to the mobile app
 * [Feature/design discussion](https://discourse.joplinapp.org/t/mobile-markdown-toolbar/26089)

# Screenshots
![Screenshot of the toolbar in landscape mode, more buttons are shown than in portrait mode](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/184793465-45e9f278-3cf1-42ce-bd08-cfd5a1cbbcd0.png)
![Screenshot of the toolbar in portrait mode: Bold, italicize, show more, spellcheck, and hide keyboard buttons are visible](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/184793494-3acd0042-b279-4c62-ba13-303d6efce87d.png)
![Screenshot of the toolbar in portrait mode, all buttons are shown, (…) icon has a grey background](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/184793515-afd00e7b-1b7a-4ed0-88e3-fb801b50f3b6.png)
![Screenshot of the toolbar in portrait mode, keyboard visible](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/184793544-22bfe5fd-1bc3-434c-963c-856edffc1fa5.png)

<!--

Please prefix the title with the platform you are targetting:

Here are some examples of good titles:

- Desktop: Resolves #123: Added new setting to change font
- Mobile, Desktop: Fixes #456: Fixed config screen error
- All: Resolves #777: Made synchronisation faster

And here's an explanation of the title format:

- "Desktop" for the Windows/macOS/Linux app (Electron app)
- "Mobile" for the mobile app (or "Android" / "iOS" if the pull request only applies to one of the mobile platforms)
- "CLI" for the CLI app

If it's two platforms, separate them with commas - "Desktop, Mobile" or if it's for all platforms, prefix with "All".

If it's not related to any platform (such as a translation, change to the documentation, etc.), simply don't add a platform.

Then please append the issue that you've addressed or fixed. Use "Resolves #123" for new features or improvements and "Fixes #123" for bug fixes.

AND PLEASE READ THE GUIDE: https://github.com/laurent22/joplin/blob/dev/CONTRIBUTING.md

-->

pr_title: Mobile: Add keyboard-activatable markdown commands (e.g. bold, italicize)
pr_body:
# Summary
 * Creates a set of commands that can be used by a future markdown toolbar.
 * Adds a find/replace dialog and a 'edit link' dialog that can be opened with `ctrl+F`/`ctrl+K`.
     * ![screenshot of find/replace dialog](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/182044957-e8f69bef-69c7-416f-827e-f61c78a65b85.png)
     * ![screenshot of edit link dialog. Has an input field for the link's title and a field for the link's URL.](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/182044996-d236f8ce-652d-461a-8f53-1edb280b1e90.png)
 * Connects some of these commands to keyboard shortcuts (e.g. ctrl+F opens a ReactNative component for find/replace, ctrl+\` toggles code, `ctrl+B` bolds).

# Keyboard shortcuts that are present in Joplin desktop, but not in this PR:
 * `ctrl+/` = comment

There may be others...

# Keyboard shortcuts **not** present in Joplin desktop, but that users might expect
 * `ctrl+H` = toggle find/replace
 * `alt+1` = toggle heading level 1
 * `alt+2` = toggle heading level 2
 * ...
 * `ctrl+shift+.` = add quote



I haven't implemented these shortcuts in this PR. `alt+1`, `alt+2`, ..., `alt+6` are **very** easy to implement. Should I add them to this PR?

pr_body:
Adds syntax highlighting for code blocks, block quotes, math in the mobile beta editor. ![Screenshot of a math note in an emulator](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/180479912-46fd709d-b8a6-471a-9782-410209369489.png) This is a refactored version of #6607. # Additional screenshots ![Screenshot of the sample text, light mode enabled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/175483529-8b1053d7-f449-4102-b8c3-08396118e46d.png) ![Screenshot of the sample text, dark mode enabled](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/46334387/175527714-96f557c2-da34-4784-9beb-0db48ad5ac0e.png) # Testing The text used in the screenshot is the following:
Text used in additional screenshots section ````markdown # Summary * The goal of this note is to demonstrate $\TeX$, `code`, and _other_ styling in the beta editor. # $\TeX$ Highlighting As can be seen, $\text{both numbers (e.g. 0, 1, 2)}$ and commands are highlighted. The highlighter uses [lezer](https://lezer.codemirror.net) to do parsing (it's the backend that CodeMirror 6 uses). The math highlighting supports both inline and block math. For example, > The Cauchy integral theorem states that, given some $z \in \mathbb{C}$ and $r \in \mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}$, > if $f : \mathbb{C} \to \mathbb{C}$ is analytic in $B_r(z_0)$, then, > $$ > f(z) = \oint_{\partial B_r(z_0)} \frac{f(w)}{(w - z)^{n+1}} dw > $$ Testing escaped: $\$$. It works! $$ % As a result of syntax highlighting, comments are also styled. \text{\TeX works inside and outside of block quotes.} $$ $$ 3 + 3 \neq 7 $$ $3+3 = 6$ # `Code` highlighting ```html

Code highlighting

This is an example of highlighted HTML.

$$ \TeX isn't highlighted in HTML blocks. $$ ``` ``` Code with no language. ``` ```js "use strict"; (function() { alert("Testing!"); })(); ``` ````
